Sentencas: The influence of chemically induced expansion on the fracture damage of a nonstoichiometric oxide (ceria) based solid oxide fuel cell (SOFC) single cell laminate was investigated by using numerical stress analyses under oxidizing/reducing gradient condition.
Titulo: Fracture process of nonstoichiometric oxide based solid oxide fuel cell under oxidizing/reducing gradient conditions

Sentencas: The single cell examined in this study was composed of electrolyte (Ce0.8Sm0.2O2-delta), anode (Cermets of Ni-Ce0.8Sm0.2O2-delta).
Titulo: Fracture process of nonstoichiometric oxide based solid oxide fuel cell under oxidizing/reducing gradient conditions
Fracture process of nonstoichiometric oxide based solid oxide fuel cell under oxidizing/reducing gradient conditions

Sentencas: The finite element method (FEM) was employed to calculate the residual stress, thermal stresses, and chemically induced expansion stresses for the single cell.
Titulo: Fracture process of nonstoichiometric oxide based solid oxide fuel cell under oxidizing/reducing gradient conditions

Sentencas: The residual and thermal stresses were calculated touch smaller than the fracture strength of the individual components of the single cell.
Titulo: Fracture process of nonstoichiometric oxide based solid oxide fuel cell under oxidizing/reducing gradient conditions

Sentencas: On the other hand, the chemically induced expansion stresses were shown to remarkably increase for the temperature range greater than 973 K and accounted their magnitude for primary part of the induced stress.
Titulo: Fracture process of nonstoichiometric oxide based solid oxide fuel cell under oxidizing/reducing gradient conditions

Sentencas: It was shown from the FEM that the maximum circumferential stress induced in the single cell exceeded the fracture strength of the individual components at the onset of the fracture damage detect by acoustic emission (AE) method.
Titulo: Fracture process of nonstoichiometric oxide based solid oxide fuel cell under oxidizing/reducing gradient conditions
